 United Kingdom, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantock's Close, Clifton, Bristol, B88 ITS, United Kingdom; O'Doherty, S., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol, United Kingdom, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantock's Close, Clifton, Bristol, B88 ITS, United Kingdom; Simmonds, P.G., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol, United Kingdom, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantock's Close, Clifton, Bristol, B88 ITS, United Kingdom","The first calibrated high-frequency, high-precision, in situ atmospheric and archived air measurements of the fumigant sulfuryl fluoride (SO <inf>2</inf>F<inf>2</inf>) have been made as part of the Advanced Global Atmospheric Gas Experiment (AGAGE) program. The global tropospheric background concentration of SO<inf>2</inf>F<inf>2</inf> has increased by 5 ± 1% per year from ∼0.3 ppt (parts per trillion, dry air mol fraction) in 1978 to ∼1.35 ppt in May 2007 in the Southern Hemisphere, and from ∼1.08 ppt in 1999 to ∼1.53 ppt in May 2007 in the Northern Hemisphere. The SO <inf>2</inf>F<inf>2</inf> interhemispheric concentration ratio was 1.13 ± 0.02 from 1999 to 2007. Two-dimensional 12-box model inversions yield global total and global oceanic uptake atmospheric lifetimes of 36 ± 11 and 40 ± 13 years, respectively, with hydrolysis in the ocean being the dominant sink, in good agreement with 35 ± 14 years from a simple oceanic uptake calculation using transfer velocity and solubility. Modeled SO<inf>2</inf>F <inf>2</inf> emissions rose from ∼0.6 Gg/a in 1978 to ∼ 1.9 Gg/a in 2007, but estimated industrial production exceeds these modeled emissions by an average of ∼50%. This discrepancy cannot be explained with a hypothetical land sink in the model, suggesting that only ∼2/3 of the manufactured SO<inf>2</inf>F<inf>2</inf> is actually emitted into the atmosphere and that ∼/3 may be destroyed during fumigation. With mean SO<inf>2</inf>F <inf>2</inf> tropospheric mixing ratios of ∼ 1.4 ppt, its radiative forcing is small and it is probably an insignificant sulfur source to the stratosphere. However, with a high global warming potential similar to CFC-11, and likely increases in its future use, continued atmospheric monitoring of SO <inf>2</inf>F<inf>2</inf> is warranted. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospherics; Global warming; Ocean engineering; Oceanography; Sulfur; Sulfur compounds; Troposphere; Upper atmosphere; Atmospheric lifetime; Atmospheric monitoring; Background concentration; Box models; Concentration ratio; Dry air; Global warming potential; High frequency HF; High-precision; In-situ; Industrial production; Mol fraction; Northern Hemispheres; Oceanic uptake; Parts per trillion; Radiative forcing; Sink-in; Southern Hemisphere; Sulfur source; Transfer velocity; Tropospheric mixing ratio; Industrial emissions; atmospheric pollution; CFC; concentration (composition); fluoride; fumigation; global warming; mixing ratio; numerical model; radiative forcing; solubility; source-sink dynamics; sulfur; sulfur emission; troposphere",,,,,,"Bousquet, P., Hauglustaine, D.A., Peylin, P., Carouge, C., Ciais, P., Two decades of OH variability as inferred by an inversion of atmospheric transport and chemistry of methyl chloroform (2005) Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 5 (10), pp. 2635-2656; Broecker, W.S., Peng, T.H., Gas-exchange rates between air and sea (1974) Tellus, 26 (1-2), pp. 21-35; Cady, G.H., Misra, S., Hydrolysis of sulfuryl fluoride (1974) Inorg Chem., 13 (4), pp. 837-841. , dorl0.1021/ic50134a016; (2005) Sulfuryl Fluonde (Vikanek), Risk Characterization Document, III, Environmental Fate, , California Environmental Protection Agency final draft report, Dep. of Pestic. Regulat., Environ. Monit, Branch, Sacramento, Calif; Chin, M., Davis, D.D., A reanalysis of carbonyl sulfide as a source of stratospheric background sulfur aerosol (1995) J Geophys. Res, 100 (D5), pp. 8993-9005. , doi:10.1029/95JD00275; Collett, J